               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-197" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-197" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-197" type="surname" value="PHELPS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-197" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA PHELPS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Phelps, who keeps the Red Lion public-house, York-street, St. James's. The prisoner was our pot-boy for five or six months—on the 11th of October I saw him at the bar-—he told me he wanted change for a sovereign, and a quartern of brandy for Mrs. Hunt, who is a customer—I gave him the brandy in a half-pint pot, with seven half-crowns and 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he went out with it—I gave it him to give her change—he was to bring me a sovereign for it—he never brought it back—I saw no more of him till he was apprehended.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-198" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-198" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-198" type="surname" value="HUNT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-198" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY HUNT</persName>
                  </hi>. I deal with Mr. Phelps. On the 11th of October I did not desire the prisoner to bring me any brandy or change for a sovereign—he never brought any thing of the kind to our house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
